In the accounts handed down to us, Van Eyck is de- scribed as a elever chemist, and it is stated that he was continually consulting works upon that science for in- formation. The works of the Arab chemists had be- come known: Albertus Magnus, Roger Bacon, Arnold of Villa Nova, Raymond Lully, had all lived and written upon the “ Magnum Opus‚'’ the basis of which rested upon sublimation and distillation, by means of which the elixir, spirit, or excellence of all things were to be extracted. The words of Lomazzo, which we have · quot-ed above, would therefore probably bear a literal meaning.

Leonardo da Vinci is stated to have followed the manner of colouring invented by John of Bruges, and to have thinned his oil by means of alembics. This, I was convinced, intended, that Leonardo distilled the oil (he himself mentions walnut oil) for the purpose of painting.
